#Scaling fonts
1.Absolute size
2.Relative size

1.Absolute size
*Sets the text to a specified size.
*Does not allow a user to change the text size in all browsers.
*Useful when the physical size of the output is known.
*Absolute font sizes generally use fixed values, such as pixels(px), to specify text sizes.
Examples:
	h1{
	    font-size:40px;
 	  }

	h2{
	    font-size:30px;
 	  }

	p{
	    font-size:14px;
 	  }

2.Relative size
*Sets the size relative to surrounding elements.
*Allows a user to change the text size in browsers.
*Setting font sizes using the em size enables users to resize the text and is often a preferred alternative to px. 1em is equal to the default text size of browsers, 16px.
Examples:
	h1{
	    font-size:2.5em; /*40px/16=2.5em */
 	  }

	h2{
	    font-size:1.875em; /*30px/16=1.875em */
 	  }

	p{
	    font-size:0.875em; /*14px/16=0.875em */;
 	  }
 
• Much like em, using percent % as a unit is also a highly responsive approach to developing content.
• It’s much easier for visitors to use scalable text that can display on any device.
	   

